<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="396" pageId="1" pageNumber="394" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1117,2043]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1225,1251]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Description.</emphasis>
Exuviae pale to light-brown (
<figureCitation box="[684,764,1225,1251]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1465,1489]" captionTargetBox="[157,1426,188,1429]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1441]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Acanthagrion truncatum: (a) dorsal habitus of exuvia; (b) detail of right cephalic lobe; (c) antenna; (d) dorsal view of prementum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283602" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283602/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Fig. 1a</figureCitation>
), F-0 larvae overall coloration light to dark-brown (
<figureCitation box="[1352,1421,1225,1251]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1492,1516]" captionTargetBox="[190,1391,389,1457]" captionTargetId="figure-110@3.[184,1404,381,1469]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Acanthagrion truncatum: dorsal habitus of female (a–b) and male (c) F-0 larvae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283604" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283604/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); slender; femora with light-brown bands; caudal lamellae long, 50–59% of total body length (
<figureCitation box="[1191,1281,1261,1287]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1465,1489]" captionTargetBox="[157,1426,188,1429]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1441]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Acanthagrion truncatum: (a) dorsal habitus of exuvia; (b) detail of right cephalic lobe; (c) antenna; (d) dorsal view of prementum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283602" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283602/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figs. 1a</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1294,1311,1261,1287]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1492,1516]" captionTargetBox="[190,1391,389,1457]" captionTargetId="figure-110@3.[184,1404,381,1469]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Acanthagrion truncatum: dorsal habitus of female (a–b) and male (c) F-0 larvae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283604" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283604/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1117,2043]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">
<emphasis box="[199,260,1297,1323]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Head</emphasis>
. Subpentagonal (similar to other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1876" box="[636,790,1297,1323]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Acanthagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="394" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[636,790,1297,1323]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Acanthagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), 0.55–0.60 as wide as long, wider than thorax and abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[214,305,1333,1359]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1465,1489]" captionTargetBox="[157,1426,188,1429]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1441]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Acanthagrion truncatum: (a) dorsal habitus of exuvia; (b) detail of right cephalic lobe; (c) antenna; (d) dorsal view of prementum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283602" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283602/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figs. 1a</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[317,334,1333,1359]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1492,1516]" captionTargetBox="[190,1391,389,1457]" captionTargetId="figure-110@3.[184,1404,381,1469]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Acanthagrion truncatum: dorsal habitus of female (a–b) and male (c) F-0 larvae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283604" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283604/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">2</figureCitation>
). In ventral view, overall shape of labrum concave anteriorly, with minute setae on anterior margin and a fine crenulation on surface; clypeus, frons and vertex smoothly rounded, glabrous with minute setae. Occipital margin widely concave, nearly straight at middle; cephalic lobes rounded, bulging at the postocular portion, with several short spines (
<figureCitation box="[394,471,1441,1467]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1465,1489]" captionTargetBox="[157,1426,188,1429]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1441]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Acanthagrion truncatum: (a) dorsal habitus of exuvia; (b) detail of right cephalic lobe; (c) antenna; (d) dorsal view of prementum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283602" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283602/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
a–b, 2). Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[684,765,1441,1467]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1465,1489]" captionTargetBox="[157,1426,188,1429]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1441]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Acanthagrion truncatum: (a) dorsal habitus of exuvia; (b) detail of right cephalic lobe; (c) antenna; (d) dorsal view of prementum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283602" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283602/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Fig. 1c</figureCitation>
) moderately long and filiform, 7-segmented, all segments uniformly colored light-brown to brown, scape and pedicel light-brown, cylindrical, 3rd antennomere the longest, proportional lengths of antennomeres: 0.62, 0.86, 1.0, 0.69, 0.50, 0.35, 0.14. Compound eyes rounded, medium sized, slightly wider than long, laterally prominent (
<figureCitation box="[738,816,1549,1575]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1492,1516]" captionTargetBox="[190,1391,389,1457]" captionTargetId="figure-110@3.[184,1404,381,1469]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Acanthagrion truncatum: dorsal habitus of female (a–b) and male (c) F-0 larvae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283604" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283604/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
a–c). Mandibles formula R 1+2345 y a / L 1+2345 a b, where b&gt;a (
<figureCitation box="[286,363,1585,1612]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1330,1354]" captionTargetBox="[159,1432,187,1302]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[151,1436,181,1307]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Acanthagrion truncatum: (a) dorsolateral view of right labial palp; internal view of right (b) and left (c) mandibles; femora: pro- (d), meso- (e), meta- (f)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283606" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283606/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figs. 3</figureCitation>
b–c). Maxilla: galeolacinia with six teeth, three of them in the dorsal portion slightly incurved, medial one slightly longer, with a basal row of 6–8 minute setae; three ventral teeth of different size and robustness being the medial the longest and the basal one roughly vestigial: apical tooth 0.50, median one 1.0, basal tooth 0.1. Prementum-postmentum articulation slightly surpassing posterior margin of prothoracic coxae; prementum (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1465,1489]" captionTargetBox="[157,1426,188,1429]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1441]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Acanthagrion truncatum: (a) dorsal habitus of exuvia; (b) detail of right cephalic lobe; (c) antenna; (d) dorsal view of prementum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283602" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283602/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Fig. 1d</figureCitation>
) longer than wide, roughly pentagonal, lateral margins slightly concave, divergent apically, laterodorsally with a row of seven (or eight) spiniform setae and a group of three minute spines on the base of each palp; ligula tip prominent, rounded, finely crenulated; two long premental setae to each side of midline, plus a minute one on 80% of specimens (54% on left side only, 26% on both sides); 20% of specimens with two long premental setae on each side, lacking the minute one. Dorsal view of labial palps (
<figureCitation box="[802,882,1873,1900]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1465,1489]" captionTargetBox="[157,1426,188,1429]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1441]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Acanthagrion truncatum: (a) dorsal habitus of exuvia; (b) detail of right cephalic lobe; (c) antenna; (d) dorsal view of prementum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283602" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283602/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Fig. 1d</figureCitation>
) with four long setae each, in anterior view (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1330,1354]" captionTargetBox="[159,1432,187,1302]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[151,1436,181,1307]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Acanthagrion truncatum: (a) dorsolateral view of right labial palp; internal view of right (b) and left (c) mandibles; femora: pro- (d), meso- (e), meta- (f)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283606" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283606/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Fig. 3a</figureCitation>
), apical lobe divided into a dorsal and a ventral branches: dorsal branch squarely truncate, composed of three small teeth, of more or less of same size and robustness; ventral branch with a well-developed end hook, with its anterior margin finely crenulate; ventral margin of palp finely crenulate; movable hook slightly less than half of labial palp length, with acute apex, lacking basal setae.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283602" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4283602" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283602/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="395" startId="2.[151,250,1465,1489]" targetBox="[157,1426,188,1429]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1465,1525]" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1465,1489]" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1876" box="[281,530,1465,1489]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Acanthagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="2" pageNumber="395" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncatum">
<emphasis box="[281,530,1465,1489]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">Acanthagrion truncatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: (a) dorsal habitus of exuvia; (b) detail of right cephalic lobe; (c) antenna; (d) dorsal view of prementum.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1571,2030]" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">
<emphasis box="[199,280,1571,1597]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">Thorax</emphasis>
. Uniformly light-brown, mostly darker on the sutures, subtrapezoidal, glabrous on the medial portion; posterior margin smoothly concave with small setae on each lateral side; anterior and posterior wing sheaths reaching anterior margin and mid S4, respectively (not stretched individuals). Legs (
<figureCitation box="[1102,1193,1643,1669]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1465,1489]" captionTargetBox="[157,1426,188,1429]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[151,1436,181,1441]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Acanthagrion truncatum: (a) dorsal habitus of exuvia; (b) detail of right cephalic lobe; (c) antenna; (d) dorsal view of prementum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283602" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283602/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">Figs. 1a</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1207,1221,1643,1669]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1492,1516]" captionTargetBox="[190,1391,389,1457]" captionTargetId="figure-110@3.[184,1404,381,1469]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Acanthagrion truncatum: dorsal habitus of female (a–b) and male (c) F-0 larvae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283604" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283604/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">2</figureCitation>
a–c, 3d–f) long, tip of metathoracic tarsi almost reaching S10 when extended, slender, pale with apical and basal bands on all femora; dorsal and ventral borders of femora with a row of spiniform setae (6–7 pro-, 6–8 meso- and 11–12 on metafemur), an external row of 5–8 spiniform setae on prothoracic femora. Tibiae sparsely spined on internal surface, bearing several setae which increase in density towards the apex with&gt;10 tridentate setae. Tarsi about 0.50 of tibiae, with two ventral rows of setae, claws with acute apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1571,2030]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,150,358]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="396" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">
<emphasis box="[199,305,1859,1885]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Covered with minute spines on dorsal and ventral surfaces of S2–10 and S9–10 apical margins; S1–8 with disrupted parallel stripes on middorsal line (as in 
<figureCitation box="[785,864,1895,1922]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1492,1516]" captionTargetBox="[190,1391,389,1457]" captionTargetId="figure-110@3.[184,1404,381,1469]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Acanthagrion truncatum: dorsal habitus of female (a–b) and male (c) F-0 larvae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283604" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283604/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
b–c), in some specimens only dark dots on apical mediodorsal segments; S3–7 with a prominent lateral carina. In ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[1019,1101,1931,1957]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,191,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[151,1436,181,1883]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Acanthagrion truncatum: ventral (a) and lateral (b) views of male gonapophyses; ventral (c) and lateroventral (d) views of female gonapophyses; left lateral views of median (e) and lateral (f) lamellae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283608" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283608/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">Fig. 4a</figureCitation>
), male gonapophyses, sharply pointed, reaching ca. basal 0.4 of sternum 10, bearing 5–6 spines each; in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[1115,1198,1967,1994]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,191,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[151,1436,181,1883]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Acanthagrion truncatum: ventral (a) and lateral (b) views of male gonapophyses; ventral (c) and lateroventral (d) views of female gonapophyses; left lateral views of median (e) and lateral (f) lamellae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283608" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283608/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="395">Fig. 4b</figureCitation>
), male gonapophyses obliquely directed. Female gonapophyses slightly surpassing S10 posterior margin, bearing two rows of minute spines on each valve (
<figureCitation box="[409,490,151,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,191,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[151,1436,181,1883]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Acanthagrion truncatum: ventral (a) and lateral (b) views of male gonapophyses; ventral (c) and lateroventral (d) views of female gonapophyses; left lateral views of median (e) and lateral (f) lamellae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283608" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283608/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="396">Figs. 4</figureCitation>
c–d). Caudal lamellae (
<figureCitation box="[758,838,151,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,191,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[151,1436,181,1883]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Acanthagrion truncatum: ventral (a) and lateral (b) views of male gonapophyses; ventral (c) and lateroventral (d) views of female gonapophyses; left lateral views of median (e) and lateral (f) lamellae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283608" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283608/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="396">Figs. 4</figureCitation>
e–f) 8.5–9 times longer than widest part, measuring 50–59% of total body length; nodus at 0.6–0.62 of lamella length; ventral margin of antenodal portion of lateral lamella with&gt;30 spines, dorsal margin bearing 2–3 spines; dorsal margin of antenodal portion of median lamella with four minute spines, ventral margin bearing&gt;20 spines, increasing in size towards the nodus. Male cerci conical, dorsal margin nearly straight, ventral margin rounded, blunt-tipped (
<figureCitation box="[963,1048,295,322]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,191,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[151,1436,181,1883]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Acanthagrion truncatum: ventral (a) and lateral (b) views of male gonapophyses; ventral (c) and lateroventral (d) views of female gonapophyses; left lateral views of median (e) and lateral (f) lamellae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283608" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283608/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="396">Fig. 4b</figureCitation>
); female cerci with apex less blunt but not acute (
<figureCitation box="[311,395,331,358]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,191,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[151,1436,181,1883]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Acanthagrion truncatum: ventral (a) and lateral (b) views of male gonapophyses; ventral (c) and lateroventral (d) views of female gonapophyses; left lateral views of median (e) and lateral (f) lamellae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283608" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283608/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="396">Fig. 4d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4283604" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4283604" box="[151,1098,1492,1516]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4283604/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="396" startId="3.[151,250,1492,1516]" targetBox="[190,1391,389,1457]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1098,1492,1516]" box="[151,1098,1492,1516]" pageId="3" pageNumber="396">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1492,1516]" pageId="3" pageNumber="396">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1876" box="[281,531,1492,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Acanthagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncatum">
<emphasis box="[281,531,1492,1516]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="396">Acanthagrion truncatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: dorsal habitus of female (a–b) and male (c) F-0 larvae.
